Annotation.note:
A problem posed at International Mathematical Olympiad:

Let $M$ be a point on AB, $AMCD$ and $MBEF$ squares to the same side
of $g(AB)$ and $N$ the intersection point of their circumscribed
circles, different from $M$.
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(i)] Show that $g(AF)$ and $g(BC)$ intersect at $N$.
\item[(ii)] Show that all lines $g(MN)$ for various $M$ meet at a
common point. 
\end{enumerate}

\begin{keywords}
geometry theorem proving
\end{keywords}
